  "final_answer": "Based on my analysis of Il Messaggero across July 1943, I now have enough information to provide a comprehensive answer. Let me compile my findings on the balance between war and domestic politics coverage across the five ISO weeks.\n\nWEEK 1943-W26: war_fraction=0.85\nWEEK 1943-W27: war_fraction=0.90\nWEEK 1943-W28: war_fraction=0.88\nWEEK 1943-W29: war_fraction=0.75\nWEEK 1943-W30: war_fraction=0.45\n\nThe balance between war coverage and domestic politics coverage in Il Messaggero underwent a dramatic transformation during July 1943, shifting from overwhelming focus on military operations to intense coverage of the regime transition following Mussolini's fall on July 25.\n\n**Weeks 26-27 (June 28-July 11): War Dominance**\n\nThe first two weeks of July were characterized by nearly complete war coverage saturation. Week 26 (June 28-July 4) featured extensive reporting on aerial bombardments of Sicily and Sardegna, with daily bulletins from the Comando Supremo (article 1943-07-02_a003, 1943-07-04_a014). Domestic politics was limited to coverage of Mussolini's June 24 speech to the Party Directorate, published July 5 (1943-07-05_a001), which itself focused on war mobilization and resistance. Week 27 (July 5-11) saw intensified war coverage as Allied invasion preparations became evident, with articles emphasizing defensive readiness and the Eastern Front battles around Kursk (1943-07-07_a018, 1943-07-07_a024).\n\n**Week 28 (July 12-18): Sicily Campaign Peak**\n\nThe Allied invasion of Sicily on July 10 dominated coverage throughout this week. Headlines like \"La battaglia in Sicilia\" (1943-07-14_a018) detailed fierce fighting by Italian-German forces. Daily war bulletins reported ship sinkings, aircraft losses, and ground combat. The newspaper published extensive German and Italian military communiqués, with minimal domestic political content beyond routine administrative announcements. War economy mobilization received some attention (1943-07-04_a011 on industrial production continuity).\n\n**Week 29 (July 19-25): Rome Bombing Shifts Balance**\n\nThis week marked the beginning of transition. The July 19 American bombing of Rome, particularly the destruction of the Basilica of San Lorenzo (1943-07-20_a002, 1943-07-20_a004, 1943-07-22_a088), introduced significant domestic civilian-front coverage alongside continuing Sicily battle reports (1943-07-20_a005, 1943-07-24_a007). The Pope's visit to devastated neighborhoods received prominent coverage. The Gran Consiglio meeting of July 24 and its aftermath began appearing, though war bulletins continued daily. The balance shifted to approximately 75% war content as domestic political crisis emerged.\n\n**Week 30 (July 26-August 1): Regime Transition Dominates**\n\nThe dramatic reversal occurred after July 25. The July 27 issue led with \"La composizione del Governo Badoglio\" (1943-07-27_a000) and devoted extensive coverage to popular demonstrations across Italy (1943-07-27_a021). The newspaper published the Gran Consiglio's order of the day and voting results (1943-07-27_a006), Badoglio's proclamations (1943-07-27_a048), and international reactions to the regime change. July 29 coverage included the dissolution of the Fascist Party and abrogation of the Gran Consiglio law (1943-07-29_a016). War coverage continued but was relegated to secondary status, with Sicily bulletins (1943-07-31_a039) sharing space with extensive domestic political reorganization news. The war fraction dropped to approximately 45% as the newspaper navigated the delicate transition from fascist to monarchist-military government while maintaining the \"la guerra continua\" message.\n\nThis shift reflects not merely editorial choice but the existential political crisis that overtook purely military concerns in the final week of July 1943, as Italy's twenty-year fascist regime collapsed amid military disaster.",
